So, if you tell AMQP that you want to ack your messages, it won't send you more than prefetchCount pending messages before you have to ack. This library, prior to this pull request, supposes that prefetchCount == 1, which means that you only get one message, and won't get the next one until you ack it. That's what shift() does, it acks the last message you got. 

If you want to increase prefetchCount to larger than 1 (or 0 for unlimited), you won't be able to use shift() anymore. This is because every time you get a message, its marked as the "last message", and shift will only ack the "last message". So suppose you are delivered ten messages m0, m1 ... m9 before you get a chance to ack any of them. Then you call shift() per each message, but that will send acks for m9 only since its marked as "last message". 

That's why I added the message object as the last argument in the subscribe callback. You can acknowledge each messge object specifically using message.acknowledge() and without using shift() at all. Here's an example:

var q = connection.queue('MyQueue', {passive: true, autodelete: false}, function(queue) { 
    console.log("Queue " + queue.name + " is open");
    q.subscribe({ack: true,  prefetchCount: 10 }, function (json, headers, deliveryInfo, message) {
        console.log("Received message : " + json);
        message.acknowledge();
    });
});

This will ack m0, m1, m2, etc...

